titleproper.value:
Guide to the Utility Workers Union of America, Local 1-2 Records
                    <num>WAG.131</num>

author.value: Finding aid prepared by Maria Concepcion, Jane Latour and Gail Malmgreen

creation.value:
This finding aid was produced using the Archivists' Toolkit
                <date>2012-03-29T21:45-0400</date>

unittitle.value: Utility Workers Union of America, Local 1-2 Records

abstract.label: Abstract
abstract.value: Local 1-2 of the Utility Workers Union of America evolved out of the Utility Workers Organizing Committee (UWOC) established by the Congress of Industrial Organizations (CIO) in 1938. In 1946, with more than 180 locals organized nationwide, the UWOC transformed itself into the Utility Workers Union of America, CIO. The collection includes: by-laws, minutes, correspondence, election records, bargaining records, and general files from 1927 and 1941 to 1995.

p.value:
Published citations should take the following form: 
                <lb/>
                <lb/>Identification of item, date; Collection name; Collection number; box number; folder number; 
                <lb/>Tamiment Library/Robert F. Wagner Labor Archives 
                <lb/>Elmer Holmes Bobst Library 
                <lb/>70 Washington Square South 
                <lb/>New York, NY 10012, New York University Libraries.

<list>
                    <item>For a more detailed history of the Local see the typescript survey report (Harry Van Arsdale Labor Records Project, Survey #387) produced by Jane Latour for the Robert F. Wagner Labor Archives in 1991.</item>
                    <item></item>
                    <item></item>
                    <item></item>
                </list>

<emph render="bold">Series VI</emph>: General Files (1927; 1941-1994, arranged alphabetically). 
                <lb/>This series includes both correspondence and a wide variety of printed materials illustrated many aspects of local union activity, as well as general subjects related to the industry, or to the interests of individuals officers. Intra-union affairs are represented in files on African-American and Cuban workers at ConEd, efforts by the Progressive Labor Party to influence Local members, Local financial records, and legislative files. Several files record the Local's dealings with individual employers other than ConEd (small numbers of Local members were employed by private companies). Several files from the 1940s detail organizing efforts within ConEd which resulted in the replacement of older company unions by the Brotherhood of Consolidated Edison Employees.
